      "response": "\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nI investigated `src/be_vm.c` around the VM opcode handlers and traced the failing script `tests/bitwise.be`.\n\nThe test contains:\n\n```berry\na = 11\n...\nassert(~a == -12)\nassert(~11 == -12)\n```\n\nThe bytecode reaches the VM `FLIP` opcode for `~a`. At that point the VM register holding `a` contains:\n\n```text\nR1.v.i = 11\nR1.type = BE_INT\n```\n\nThe instruction is the `FLIP` opcode, whose comment in `be_opcodes.h` says:\n\n```c\nOPCODE(FLIP),       /*  A, B     |   R(A) <- ~RK(B) */\n```\n\nBut the implementation in `src/be_vm.c` is:\n\n```c\nopcase(FLIP): {\n    bvalue *dst = RA(), *a = RKB();\n    if (var_isint(a)) {\n        var_setint(dst, -a->v.i);\n    } else if (var_isinstance(a)) {\n        ins_unop(vm, \"~\", *RKB());\n        reg = vm->reg;\n        *RA() = *vm->top; /* copy result to dst */\n    } else {\n        unop_error(vm, \"~\", a);\n    }\n    dispatch();\n}\n```\n\nFor integer operands, `FLIP` is using arithmetic negation:\n\n```c\n-a->v.i\n```\n\ninstead of bitwise complement:\n\n```c\n~a->v.i\n```\n\nSo when the test evaluates:\n\n```berry\n~11\n```\n\nthe VM computes:\n\n```text\n-11\n```\n\ninstead of the expected bitwise result:\n\n```text\n~11 == -12\n```\n\nThis makes the assertion false. The program does not crash with a signal; it runs to completion / exits through the normal libc frames, but the test oracle reports incorrect behavior because the interpreter implemented the `~` operator incorrectly.\n\nThe neighboring `NEG` opcode correctly uses arithmetic negation:\n\n```c\nopcase(NEG): {\n    ...\n    if (var_isint(a)) {\n        var_setint(dst, -a->v.i);\n    }\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nThe `FLIP` handler appears to have been copied from `NEG` and not changed for the integer case.\n\nROOT CAUSE: `src/be_vm.c:746` implements the integer `FLIP` / `~` opcode as arithmetic negation, `-a->v.i`, instead of bitwise complement, `~a->v.i`. Therefore `~11` evaluates to `-11` instead of `-12`, causing `tests/bitwise.be` assertions to fail.\n\nLOCAL FIX:\n\n```diff\ndiff --git a/src/be_vm.c b/src/be_vm.c\n--- a/src/be_vm.c\n+++ b/src/be_vm.c\n@@ -743,7 +743,7 @@ static void vm_exec(bvm *vm)\n         opcase(FLIP): {\n             bvalue *dst = RA(), *a = RKB();\n             if (var_isint(a)) {\n-                var_setint(dst, -a->v.i);\n+                var_setint(dst, ~a->v.i);\n             } else if (var_isinstance(a)) {\n                 ins_unop(vm, \"~\", *RKB());\n                 reg = vm->reg;\n```\n\nGLOBAL FIX: Avoid hand-written duplicated opcode logic for unary integer operators. Introduce a shared helper or macro that makes the intended primitive operation explicit and testable, for example:\n\n```c\n#define int_unop_block(op, opname)                 \\\n    bvalue *dst = RA(), *a = RKB();                \\\n    if (var_isint(a)) {                            \\\n        var_setint(dst, op a->v.i);                \\\n    } else if (var_isinstance(a)) {                \\\n        ins_unop(vm, opname, *RKB());              \\\n        reg = vm->reg;                             \\\n        *RA() = *vm->top;                          \\\n    } else {                                       \\\n        unop_error(vm, opname, a);                 \\\n    }\n\nopcase(NEG): {\n    int_unop_block(-, \"-\");\n    dispatch();\n}\nopcase(FLIP): {\n    int_unop_block(~, \"~\");\n    dispatch();\n}\n```\n\nAlso add VM-level regression tests for every primitive unary opcode, specifically checking that `~0 == -1`, `~1 == -2`, and `~11 == -12`, so copy/paste mistakes between `NEG` and `FLIP` are caught immediately.",
